description.text:
I designed these word cubes for use in my kindergarten class to practice decoding CVC (consonant, vowel, consonant) words. Each word cube prints as one piece, with no assembly required, but allows the middle cube to spin freely. Each cube creates 16 different real and nonsense words, all decodable using basic phonics (i.e. all stops and no fricatives such as "soft" C or G in the initial slot).

Also included for download is a worksheet for students to record their words, and then write a sentence including at least one of the words recorded.

Note: Normally I wince when I see kindergarten activities using only uppercase letters, but since caps are what's available on Tinkercad by default, I went with it and just ask my kiddos to write in lower case when doing this activity.

description.text: 1/2/4-rail power bus with as many terminals as you want.

Customize and select how many rails and slots you want, export an STL and print it. Once printed, you'll need:
  • one M4 rod per rail, 9 millimeters per slot on that rail
  • one M3 nut per slot
  • one M3x10 cap screw per slot
    • To assemble, just put the M4 rod in through the hole on the side, drop one M3 nut in each nut trap and screw in the screws from the sides. Insert cables from the top/bottom and tighten the screws, all done. You can of course use longer screws, but they will stick out, which you probably don't want. (Especially if you're doing high voltage stuff...)

description.text:
A full sized coffee table for you lucky people who have a printer big enough to print one.
And for those who don't, well, you can always get into that small furniture fad.

Inlay pattern adapted from Craftsman Space's Interlacement Ornament pattern:
http://www.craftsmanspace.com/free-patterns/interlacement-ornament.html

Successfully printed (at different sizes and slice heights) on:

  • Stratasys Fortus 900mc - full size
  • Stratasys Fortus 450mc - reduced size
  • Zortrax 200m - tiny size
  • Flash Forge Creator I - reduced size

Support is only required in the inlay portion of the table top.
For Desktop Printers, try "WeeksB_CoffeeTable-Small.STL". It's been sized down and had the inlays deepened to offset the sizing difference.

This is my latest version of my completely 3d-printable 250 FPV racing quadcopter design. The design is very compact and is designed to not break. The control board, RC receiver, power distribution, and other things are within the 15mm between the top and bottom plates, so they are completely protected. This quadcopter is designed to be robust and reliable, even in the hardest of crashes. The arms are foldable, to increase time of impact in a crash in order to keep them from breaking. The landing gear acts as a fuse, it is likely to break in a hard crash, but also helps prevent arms and other parts from breaking, while being very easy to replace. The battery can be mounted on the top or the bottom; the battery mount part is only needed for the bottom. There is an extended version of the top plate used for mounting an FPV camera from the bottom in front. A Mobius or similar camera can be mounted on the top or bottom in addition to the FPV camera. The motor mounts have standard 12X16 mounting for 1806 motors and 16x19 mounting for 2204 motors. All hardware (except for motor mounting for 1806 motors) is M3. Metal hardware is recommended for arm mounts, (so it can be tight and arms aren't floppy), while nylon hardware is recommended for everything else so it is lighter.

This is an experimental prototype enclosure for a miniature DC motor. It is designed to be used in harsh environments, however, due to no air circulation, the motor may get hot. I havent tested it for extended use or use in harsh environments yet.
The hole for the motor shaft will need to be drilled out to fit the shaft.
The cap was not designed to be removed once installed. Removing the cap may damage the case.
Mounting holes for two different mounting options are built in. A hole for the wires is also built in.
I hope someone finds it useful.

1) Print the case and drill out the motor shaft hole just enough to allow the motor to turn freely. 
2) Install your motor into the case and solder the wires so that they route inward.
3) Print the cap and route the wires through the hole in the end cap and snap the cap on. Note : To make the enclosure more water resistant, apply some silicon into the groove on the case before snapping the cap on. Apply silicon to the hole where the wires exit the cap. To further protect the motor from water, apply some petroleum jelly to the shaft/hole.
4) Mount it onto your project and enjoy!

author: mredmon

title: Counterweight System for Trick Laser Rostock MAX METAL

description.text:
CAUTION - SAFETY FIRST!!!
You'll need to keep any small children/curious pets away from this counterweight system. Cats are especially problematic, as they may swat at the weights or try to chew the fishing line! If the line breaks, which is a possibility you must keep in mind, the weight will immediately drop, and may cause permanent injury or even death. Please keep this in mind while deciding whether or not this system is safe enough to use in your environment. If you can't keep potentially curious/destructive parties away from the printer, you might want to consider moving it!
.

INTENDED USES
This is intended for use with my magnetic arm drivetrain system and triple flying extruder platform, which have not yet been released. This section will be updated when they are.

In the mean time, if you happen to have your own flying extruder system, effector-mounted extruders, or anything else requiring that you take significant weight off the carriages, you can use this system to do so.
.

PARTS YOU'LL NEED
You'll need these V-groove bearings, these 500-gram weights (or whatever is suitable for your application if you're not building my flying extruder system), and some of this 50-pound braided fishing line. You'll also need M3 screws, 15mm or longer. You may want to use nylon locknuts to secure them in place. In that case, get screws that are long enough to accommodate the locknuts.

Parts are fixed to the frame using Unbrako #10-32 x 1/2 low-head caphead screws and 80/20 Inc T-Slot HW 10 Series 10-32 Roll-In T-Nut w/Ball Spring #3922 N.
.

PRINTING
This is all supposed to be printed as a single piece, and will definitely require support. There are three separate STLs, so if your printer can do multi-extrusion, you can have the base and arms in different colors. If your printer only does single extrusion, it's okay. In either case, you'll need to figure out how to do multi-STL prints with your slicer if you don't already know.

Use at least 3 outside loops, and at least 20% infill.
.

FISHING LINE ROUTING
The fishing line should descend from the back of the inner V-groove bearing, and it should clear the endstop mount and anything else. The fishing line MUST NOT touch ANYTHING on its way down to the carriage. If it does, the line may fray and break! In fact, it may fray even if that's not the case. It hasn't on my printer, but I can't promise it won't on anyone else's.

title: Minimal stand for BQ Aquaris E5HD Ubuntu Phone

description.text:
My design goals for this stand were something that could easily be carried very flat in a small pocket or on a keyring, with enough stability to be usable for gentle swiping, and small/fast enough to print out a zillion copies and stick them in every desk drawer and backpack compartment.

The stand "clip" section uses slight friction to provide stability and stay on the phone when picked up, but friction is not strictly required (unless in the secondary more upright angled mode pictured) - the weight of the phone pushes both down on the top of the triangle, and up on the top hat of the clip, and is thus self-supporting. The stand is angled back behind the phone slightly for balance.

Physics dictates that solid touch presses can only be achieved in the diagonally lower right half of the screen, which is perfect for "alt-tabbing" on Ubuntu touch. The stand is also balanced such that soft/gentle touches and swipes on the top left diagonal half will not tip the phone over. If you however want solid presses on the left top diagonal half, mirror image this design and print a stand for the left side as well.

Another tip for tables and slippery surfaces: store some blue-tack in the triangular section of the stand. Use it to anchor the bottom edge of the phone to the table so it doesn't slide when you swipe.

I assume this should also work fine for the Android version of the E5HD :)

title: Cable Mast for Trick Laser Rostock MAX METAL

description.text:
This cable mast allows you to route your hot end wiring without having to lash it directly to the top of the frame. It will take most of the weight of the cable, and you can take even more weight off the effector by using my strain relief mast and some paracord.

The mast and extension were printed on a Rostock MAX METAL with Trick Laser's 269mm arms. The mast is 260mm tall, so it should print okay on printers with 269, 290, and 300mm arms, although I've only printed it with 269mm arms. (Unless your printable height is less than ~280mm, you should be fine. There does have to be some leeway for the carriages to be able to move the effector from side to side.) You should print the mast and extension one at a time, as the build volume of a delta printer is highest at dead center. Move the mast in your slicer so that the center of the mast is over the center of the print surface.

The mast and extension are intended to be lashed together with zip ties, which are also used to lash the cable(s) to the inside of the mast. As this will be a long print, it's a good idea to print the calibration STL first so that you can be sure the mast and extension fit together properly!

The stabilizer piece will help keep the mast upright. It comes with a small locking bar that you can use to secure it to the mast. However, I must admit that I've lost mine, and it still works fine.

Parts are fixed to the frame using Unbrako #10-32 x 1/2 low-head caphead screws and 80/20 Inc T-Slot HW 10 Series 10-32 Roll-In T-Nut w/Ball Spring #3922 N.

Bud vase
printed using t-glase from 3dprintergear.com.au, impressive and almost see through. Small vase for buds or small flowers

This model is part of an ongoing proof of concept while I work on the image import feature of OSCADSharp.

I generated the model by feeding in a topographical image of Vermont to OSCADSharp, which generated a height-mapped 3D model composed of cubes. It took a tiny bit of tweaking though, because height is assigned based on the sum of each color. Lighter colors are taller, while darker colors are lower. (Note - the model isn't particularly accurate topographically speaking!)

The result ended up better than expected, and mine will be a fridge magnet.

This feature is not yet released in the public NuGet package. If you're interested in how the height mapping feature is coming along, feel free to follow along on GitHub or pull it down and give it a try.

https://github.com/Exolun/OSCADSharp

title: PanelDue Enclosure with Mount for Trick Laser Rostock MAX METAL

description.text:
This will allow you to mount a PanelDue to your Rostock MAX METAL. (Or something else, if you feel like modifying the mounting bracket!) It makes use of captive M3 nylon locknuts as well as M3 screws. You can use four 5mm screws for the LCD, and seven 15mm screws for everything else. You'll want to use countersunk screws for the lid. One of the illustrations shows the lid (transparent), which is countersunk to accept them. If you don't, the frame will get in the way of the screw heads.

The mounting brackets are fixed to the frame using Unbrako #10-32 x 1/2 low-head caphead screws and 80/20 Inc T-Slot HW 10 Series 10-32 Roll-In T-Nut w/Ball Spring #3922 N.

PLEASE NOTE: You MUST have your printer calibrated for dimensional accuracy. Otherwise, the screw holes probably won't line up! Everything you need to calibrate your printer's dimensional accuracy is right here.

This is a remix of dc42's enclosure. It has a few new features, and the internal screw posts should print a little bit easier.

description.text:
Download and print our Soda Bottle Thread to 3/8" NPT Male Thread Adapter and use it to create compressed air storage tanks, or for pressure testing Water Rockets.

Using these adapters, you can join any soft drink bottle with a standard 22mm neck to a 3/8" NPT Male Pipe Thread. This design uses our innovative #213 O-ring sealing system for handling high pressures, and also works with regular flat rubber washers as well.

These adapters are ideal for pressure testing water rockets, especially the type made using multiple spliced together bottles, which you can learn more about if you check out our homepage http://www.USWaterRockets.com. These adapters are also useful for anyone wishing to make a 2 Liter Bottle air storage tank.

This video shows the adapter in use: https://youtu.be/xHOR-srdI_k

Caution: You use this part at your own risk. We cannot guarantee the safety of this part due to the differences between printers and filaments. Always safety test parts like this and follow proper safety measures when dealing with compressed gasses. Use with adult supervision.

description.text:
I've added a quick version using the round one in the note below.
AND I've modified that one too :)
With just the arcs and not a continuous rim, there are sometimes bumps at the ends that mess up the measurements so here is one without the gaps. The picture shows the earlier one with gaps.
As I can easily take the build plate off for measurements, there was no need for it to hold together. This quick one makes multiple readings for adjustments much faster and uses less filament.
Also, there is a 100mm vertical test piece that needs to be run first to adjust the "DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT"

NOTE!!!!
I recommend you don't use my original, but look at this one that was based on it...
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1557870
A much better job as it is actually smooth around!

Test print for adjusting a Delta Printer that has uneven prints.
Make sure it is printed centrally on your printer.

The notes here are from torsti76 on the Deltaprintr forums, thank you :)

"Fortunately, Marlin has a (currently undocumented) cure for that (cf. https://github.com/MarlinFirmware/Marlin/issues/2159).
In short, what you should do is:
print a cylindric object of a relatively large diameter, say 100 mm
measure the dimensions in the direction of each tower
if you find they are off, adjust DELTA_DIAGONAL_ROD_TRIM_TOWER_x, where x is the number of the tower (1 - front left, 2 - front right, 3 - back)
The formula for adjustment would be:
(DIAGONAL_ROD_LENGTH intended dimension for tower x / measured dimension for tower x) - DIAGONAL_ROD_LENGTH = DELTA_DIAGONAL_ROD_TRIM_TOWER_x
Assuming you measured the dimension for the X tower (front left) to be 102 mm for your 100 mm cylinder, the formula for adjustment would be:
(255 100 / 102) - 255 = -5
So, you'd put that line in your Configuration.h:
"#define DELTA_DIAGONAL_ROD_TRIM_TOWER_1 -5"
This way you'll be able to eliminate all dimensional failures without having to painstakingly measure your printer or to modify its basic mechanical settings."

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/9rnbCDI4tTc

description.text: A tessellating bird. All the pieces are identical, and the symmetry involved is absolutely fascinating. In this one, the symmetry points are placed in an equilateral triangle, which makes the shape tessellating. If you wonder how this works, Google M C Escher and read some of the articles about his work. I don't think you'll regret it. This thing, and the Gecko (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1542107), I hope to use as a teaching aid for a practical approach to teaching symmetry.

Just a towel holder I made to hang my towels on my cupboard without drilling into it (renting). It fits the thickness of my door which is 17mm thick (perfect for 18mm).

Two versions - one piece and two pieces. For the two piece configuration you'll need:

1 x M3 nut
1 x 10-20mm M3 screw

Put the nut with a pointy end down into the slot and push it to the very bottom. If it doesn't fit snuggly to the side of the slot (width ways) it's not going to fit nicely down the bottom so I wouldn't try.

Put the screw into the large hole on the back of the mount and push it through the countersunk hole, then screw into the hole and nut you just put in.

If it doesn't fit snuggly on the door, put a little silicon pad on the inside of the mount.
